member.name: T:Microsoft.VisualStudio.PlatformUI.AbstractPoint
member.summary: Microsoft internal use only. A class that represents a point abstractly. This is useful with controls or panels that support multiple orientations. The rendering or layout code for the control or panel can be written using a single, "natural" orientation and then the point can be converted, if necessary, to the control's or panel's actual orientation as needed. This can substantially simplify rendering or layout logic.

For example, it may be most natural to write the layout code for a StackPanel using Vertical orientation since a stack in the real world is a vertical thing.The choice of natural orientation within a given context is not important, as long as the same natural orientation is used consistently throughout that context.

For example, it may be most natural to write the layout code for a StackPanel using Vertical orientation since a stack in the real world is a vertical thing.The choice of natural orientation within a given context is not important, as long as the same natural orientation is used consistently throughout that context.

member.name: P:Microsoft.VisualStudio.PlatformUI.AbstractSize.RealHeight
member.summary: The real, non-abstract height of the size. If IsNatural is true, the real height and the abstract height are the same. If IsNatural is false, the real height is the abstract width.

member.name: P:Microsoft.VisualStudio.PlatformUI.AbstractSize.RealSize

member.name: P:Microsoft.VisualStudio.PlatformUI.AbstractSize.RealWidth

member.name: T:Microsoft.VisualStudio.PlatformUI.GreedyWrapPanel
member.summary: Microsoft internal use only. This panel is very similar to a WrapPanel, but instead of wrapping when a boundary is reached, it wraps once it has enough space.For Orientation=Vertical, this means that it will use as many columns as it can, given enough children and width. For Orientation=Horizontal, it will use as many rows as it can, given enough children and height. You can also specify a maximum number of wrapping levels (columns for Vertical, rows for Horizontal) with MaxWrappingLevels.For Vertical GreedyWrapPanels, all children elements must have the same width. For Horizontal, they must all have the same height. This was done to optimize for performance. Loosening this restriction greatly increases the level of complexity with measuring and arranging the elements

member.summary: Initializes a new instance of GreedyWrapPanel.

member.name: P:Microsoft.VisualStudio.PlatformUI.GreedyWrapPanel.ActualWrappingLevels
member.summary: This property controls the direction that elements flow. If Vertical, elements flow from top to bottom. If Horizontal, elements flow from left to right.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.PlatformUI.GreedyWrapPanel.ActualWrappingLevelsProperty
member.summary: A read-only property that is the actual number of levels we are using, regardless of what MaxLevels is set to. For Orientation=Vertical, this corresponds to Columns, while for Orientation=Horizontal, this corresponds to Rows.

member.name: M:Microsoft.VisualStudio.PlatformUI.GreedyWrapPanel.ArrangeOverride(System.Windows.Size)
member.summary: This method arranges the children. For Orientation=Vertical, it uses as many columns as it can, until it reaches MaxLevels. For Orientation=Horizontal, it uses the maximum number of rows possible. However, for both, their columns or rows respectively will never be more than MaxWrappingLevels.
member.returns: The size used by this panel.
member.param: The size given this panel.

member.summary: Gets or sets the maximum wrapping levels.

member.name: M:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.AsyncPackage.Initialize
member.summary: Seal this method. Due to an almost unavoidable risk of deadlock, SetSite (which is what calls Initialize) still occurs on the UI thread even for async package. Since most async package authors would, logically, assume that Initialize happens on a b/g thread they may do expensive (synchronous) things inside of their override, defeating some of the benefit of async loads. To help lead them away from that we will seal it and thus all they can override is async initialize, which is called on the b/g thread.

member.name: M:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsColors.GetCurrentThemedColorValues
member.summary: Gets all of the current color values in a single Dictionary. This is useful for scenarios where colors are required outside the Visual Studio process or in an AppDomain other than the primary AppDomain, where all of the colors may need to be copied in bulk.
member.returns: A dictionary mapping the keys for colors to their ARGB value for the current theme.

member.summary: Gets and unsigned integer VS_RGBA value from the current theme for the given color key. The returned value has the red channel in the low byte and the alpha channel in the high byte.
member.returns: The current theme's VS_RGBA value of the named color.
member.param: The service, used to get the color's value.
The key for which to find the color.

member.name: T:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsDockStyle
member.summary: Defines constants for tool window orientation.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsDockStyle.AlwaysFloat
member.summary: If the value is , the tool window cannot be docked.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsDockStyle.Float
member.summary: If the value is , the tool window will float initially, but when the title bar is double-clicked, Orientation and Window apply, and the window will default to Tabbed.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsDockStyle.Linked
member.summary: If the value is , Orientation can be Left, Right, Top, or Bottom.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsDockStyle.MDI
member.summary: If the value is , the tool window will be linked to the multiple-document interface (MDI) area, and Window is ignored.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsDockStyle.none
member.summary: The registration attribute initializes to this value if no style is specified.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsDockStyle.Tabbed
member.summary: If the value is , Orientation can be Left or Right and tab placement can be specified.

member.name: T:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsFrameMode
member.summary: Controls the display mode of a tool window.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsFrameMode.AutoHide
member.summary: Specifies the frame mode is autohide. This value cannot be combined with other flags.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsFrameMode.Dock
member.summary: Specifies the tool window is docked. A docked tool window is attached to the side of the application window.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsFrameMode.Float
member.summary: Specifies the tool window is able to float over other windows. Floating windows can exist outside the application area.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsFrameMode.FloatOnly
member.summary: Specifies the tool window is able to float over other windows, and cannot be docked.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsFrameMode.MdiChild
member.summary: Specifies the tool window is a Multiple Document Interface (MDI) child window, and is treated in a manner similar to a document window.

member.name: T:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsFramePropID
member.summary: Specifies property identifiers for window frames, document frames, and tool window frames.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsFramePropID.AltDocData
member.summary: If this window is only editing a piece of a larger document then AltDocData is the DocData object for the piece of the document that is being edited within the window, whereas the RDTDocData is the DocData object for the entire document registered in the RDT. AltDocData objects are not registered in the RDT. Document windows that have AltDocData objects are created using the CDW_fAltDocData flag.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsFramePropID.BitmapIndex
member.summary: The index of the image to use in the bitmap strip for the window frame icon.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsFramePropID.BitmapResource

A solution load manager is able to control how projects are loaded during the Solution Open operation. It can control whether projects are loaded immediately, loaded in the background (at idle), left to be loaded if needed, or set to stay unloaded. A solution load manager is expected to implement . A common approach is to have the solution load manager package autoload for the SolutionOpening UIContext, for example, [ProvideAutoLoad(UIContextGuids.SolutionOpening)]. member.summary: An is thrown if an attempt is made to attach a child task to the created task.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsTaskContinuationOptions.ExecuteSynchronously
member.summary: The continuation task should be executed synchronously. With this option specified, the continuation is run on the same thread that causes the antecedent task to transition into its final state. If the antecedent is already complete when the continuation is created, the continuation is run on the thread creating the continuation. Only very short-running continuations should be executed synchronously.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsTaskContinuationOptions.IndependentlyCanceled
member.summary: The task can be canceled independently of any other task.

member.summary: In the case of continuation cancellation, prevents completion of the continuation until the antecedent has completed.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsTaskContinuationOptions.LongRunning
member.summary: The task is a long-running, course-grained operation. It provides a hint to the task library that oversubscription may be warranted.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsTaskContinuationOptions.None

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsTaskContinuationOptions.NotCancelable
member.summary: The continuation task cannot be canceled.

member.summary: The continuation task should not be scheduled if its antecedent was canceled. This option is not valid for multi-task continuations.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsTaskContinuationOptions.NotOnFaulted
member.summary: The continuation task should not be scheduled if its antecedent threw an unhandled exception. This option is not valid for multi-task continuations.

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsTaskContinuationOptions.NotOnRanToCompletion

member.name: F:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Shell.VsTaskContinuationOptions.OnlyOnRanToCompletion
